  "doc_id": "41224",
  "text": "Human listeners are able to segregate and recognize a sound signal from a background of acoustic interference even under adverse conditions. The auditory scene analysis (ASA) process described by Bregman involves grouping elements that are likely to have originated from the same source into a perceptual structure called an auditory stream. Our focus is on computational approaches to ASA that exploit the information to detect time-frequency (T-F) units that preserve reliable information for the target sound. Therefore, the computational goal is to estimate an ideal binary mask which selects T-F units where the target energy dominates [CITATION_1] . Such ideal binary masks have been shown to be effective front-ends for robust automatic speech recognition [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] and to provide speech intelligibility improvements for normal listeners under noisy conditions [CITATION_4] .",
